    <div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='7811#1260468710'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2009-12-10T18:11:50+00:00">Dec 10, 2009 06:11 PM UTC</time> by <b>Christopher Pipes</b><a class="anchor" name="1260468710">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>I believe that the alarm has cleared from nagios alertmon so i am closing it. I pray it doesn&#39;t come back.

**SUMMARY**

Here&#39;s a summary of what&#39;s been going on with the IFW stuff.

1. Yesterday (12/8) at about 2&#58;30 p.m. I sent a request to the IFW people&#58;

Please Change the IDC Firewall policy for subnet 129.79.14.128
(bl-129-79-14-128.reserved.iu.edu) to &#58;

URGENT REQUEST&#58; Please add the following to the list of ports allowed for
subnet 259 ASAP&#58;

Source&#58; any
Destination&#58; subnet 259, 129.79.14.128/25
Service&#58; TCP ports 15001-15006

2. They wrote back asking whether I meant VLAN 259, not subnet 259.  At about
3 p.m. I responded yes, I meant VLAN 259.

3. At about 3&#58;15 p.m. they wrote back again, asking whether I wanted all the
subnets on VLAN 259 opened for those ports -- there&#39;s a private subnet that we
don&#39;t use (unrelated to the private VLAN we use that replaces our LAN switch),
and apparently VLAN 259 still contains the 129.79.16.192/26 subnet that we
were originally assigned but didn&#39;t use because it wasn&#39;t big enough (I wasn&#39;t
aware that it was still allocated to us).  I responded at 3&#58;51 that no, we
just need it on 129.79.14.128/25.

4. There was no further response yesterday.  Today at 10&#58;42 a.m. I decided to
send them another email saying exactly what we needed again.

5. Arvind sent mail saying that we should also have this policy on the IUPUI
VLAN, which is absolutely right, so I looked at the firewall policies for the
IUPUI VLAN and saw that there were several rules that needed updating, so I
<div id='show_224689479' class=''><button class="btn">Show More</button></div><div class='detail hidden' id='detail_224689479'>decided to go through and request policy changes that had been overdue for a
while.  I did the same with the IUB policies.

6. One of the things that I discovered was that there was a new policy
granting global access on TCP port 25 to the 129.79.14.128/25 subnet (our IUB
servers).  This probably got created over Thanksgiving when Arvind requested
it&#58; they created a whole new policy rather than adding SMTP to the existing
blanket policy.  I sent a request asking that port 25 access be added to the
uber-policy (which is policy 674) and this extra policy (policy 787) be
deleted.

7. Then they finally got to our requests.  At 11&#58;09 a.m. I got a report that
the first ticket had been closed.  What I didn&#39;t know was that they&#39;d added the
rule for port 15001-15006 (for VOMS) to policy 787, rather than policy 674.
This information is not available in the &#34;ticket closed&#34; email.  At 3&#58;58 p.m.
I got an email that they had closed the ticket to add the port-25 rule to
policy 674 and delete policy 787.  This meant, of course, that port 25 access
remained the same, but our urgent VOMS request had just gotten undone.

8. I then saw in the chatroom that alarms were going off.  I scrambled to put
the pieces together, and the above is what I believe happened.  I sent an
email (copies to Arvind and Rob) in response to the &#34;ticket closed&#34; email
noting that the issue was not resolved and explaining exactly what we needed
done (including the exact change that needed to be made to policy 674).
Unfortunately it was 5&#58;00 p.m. by the time I was able to figure out what had
happened and compose the email.

So the Nagios alarms will continue to go off until the IFW people fix this.
There is now nothing more I can do, since they intentionally have no phone
number that anyone can call if there is a problem.

Soichi said &#34;Thanks for the report Tom! This makes me think, that in the future, all FW change should occur on our usual release cycle (2nd and 4th Tuesday) just in case something catastrophic happens.. but that might be overkill? (I&#39;d hate to have a policy over something that almost never occurs but *it might* occur)&#34;

Arvind said, &#34;A better idea might be to never request inst.f/w changes ... because I
doubt it&#39;ll make a huge difference if a screw up happens on a particular
day, Tom would have to continue dealing with it either way. Sorry Tom, I
feel you pain (sort off), thankfully this VOMS is not considered a high
profile service, we can get by this time, and hopefully we can have all
of this sorted out by COB today or so.&#34;
